<br>
The critical difference lies in the fact that &quot;war zone&quot; analogies are indeed applicable.  On the one hand, I do believe that the driver was responsible for his actions, and I expect he will suffer the consequences in a military court, whatever those are.  However, there are mitigating factors on his side - he was following orders (no Nazi references please, not the same situation), he was doing his job, and going out on a limb here, I'm going to say that he *probably* did not intend to kill the girl, simply frighten her into moving out of the way (the game of chicken).  On the other hand, I see a very real parallel with other human shield incidents.  You say that it cannot be compared with Iraqi human shields being bombed - I say it can.  True, at the instant the bombs are dropped the human shield doesn't really have a choice any more; he's going to die.  But the critical point is that he *chose* to remain there, despite being told over and over and over, and being able to see for himself, that staying where he was, remaining a &quot;human shield&quot; would result in his death.  This is precisely what happened to Rachel C., it just happened over a shorter time frame.  As war approaches, the &quot;bulldozer&quot; of American air strikes creeps closer and closer to Iraqi human shields, who have the option of giving up and leaving right up until the last second, when they &quot;fall down&quot; and are killed by American bombs.  Is it the American pilot's fault for killing the shield?  Is it the commander's fault who ordered the strike despite the fact that the human shield was there?  Are they responsible for the death of that person, even though they *could* delay the strike, call in ground forces, and have the human shield dragged away, all the while risking the chance that the building he was guarding will be used once again for nefarious purposes, risking the chance that opposition will be organized against the ground troops as they go in to remove the offending human shield... see where I'm going with this?<br>
<br>
In the end, the most vivid lesson to be learned is that &quot;human shield&quot; operations are just plain nutty, stupid, and useless.  If these people valued human life, they wouldn't risk their own in pointless personal crusades which accomplish nothing. <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.visveres.myguilds.com/sigs/caledhon.gif" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=caledhontelrana>Caledhon TelRana</A> at: 3/19/03 11:16:52 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#4D4D4D><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=wolvar>Wolvar</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_thatch.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>My third character is Lovawr</span><br>  Posts: 1799<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(3/19/03 11:28 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=498.topic&index=147>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Strange</span><hr size=1> Bulldozing that house was not a military imperative.  Yes, he was ordered to do it, but not &quot;at whatever cost&quot;.  If you are ordered to do something non-critical that endangers cvilian life, assuming there is time, you communicate and ask for clarification of the order and inform your superior of the additional circumstances.  The ONLY time it's acceptable not to do is if a mission will be jeapordized by delay.<br>
<br>
If it was intentional, it was murder, and NOT justified by war.<br>
<br>
I have little sympathy in general towards liberal pussy human shield types.  I think the whole concept is stupid and yes, the girl was knowingly placing her life at risk.  The context of this incident however, places the blame of her death squarely on the person that chose to kill her.  Therein lies the flaw of bombs dropping and firing range... being unable to prevent a death does not equal a choice to cause a death.  <br>
<br>
That choice to cause a death, in a military scenario, must be justified either by the imperative need to destroy the target, the inability to prevent the death, or a lack of time to clarify the order. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=tuwene>Tuwene</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Beware the paladin<br>with a map & a plan</span><br>  Posts: 482<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(3/19/03 11:33 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=498.topic&index=148>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Strange</span><hr size=1> In a &quot;war zone&quot; a soldier or fighter pilot can't wait for someone to remove all the &quot;innocent targets&quot; before that person does their job.  I agree that &quot;human shields&quot; planting their ass inside an iraqi military base are going to die, and I have no real pity for them.<br>
